6 SENATE
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 538, L.D. 1308, “Resolve, Directing the
10 Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife to Establish a Working Group to Explore
11 Opportunities to Maintain Public Access of Land”
12 Amend the resolve by striking out the title and substituting the following:
13 'Resolve, Directing the Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife and the
14 Department of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry to Examine Issues Related to
15 Public Access to Privately Owned Lands'
16 Amend the resolve by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
17 'Emergency preamble. Whereas, acts and resolves of the Legislature do not
18 become effective until 90 days after adjournment unless enacted as emergencies; and
19 Whereas, a majority of land in the State is privately owned; and
20 Whereas, the ability of residents to access these lands is in jeopardy as more and more
21 landowners are closing off access to their land; and
22 Whereas, urgent action is needed to ensure this trend is reversed; and
23 Whereas, this legislation must take effect as soon as possible to convene a working
24 group to explore opportunities to increase access and address these issues; and
25 Whereas, in the judgment of the Legislature, these facts create an emergency within
26 the meaning of the Constitution of Maine and require the following legislation as
27 immediately necessary for the preservation of the public peace, health and safety; now,
28 therefore, be it
29 Sec. 1. Working group. Resolved: That the Department of Inland Fisheries and
30 Wildlife and the Department of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry, jointly referred to
31 in this resolve as "the departments," shall convene a working group to examine issues
32 related to public access to privately owned land in the State and opportunities to expand
33 this access.
Page 1 - 132LR1460(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 538, L.D. 1308
1 Sec. 2. Working group membership. Resolved: That the working group
2 established under section 1 must be as broadly representative of interested parties and
3 groups as possible, must be geographically representative of the different regions of the
4 State and consists of at least the following 12 members:
5 1. A representative of a statewide organization representing commercial forest
6 landowners;
7 2. A representative of a statewide organization representing small woodland owners;
8 3. A representative of an organization managing recreational access to the North Maine
9 Woods;
10 4. A representative of a conservation organization that manages land or conservation
11 easements;
12 5. A representative of an agricultural organization;
13 6. A representative of a statewide organization representing Maine guides;
14 7. A representative of the tourism and outdoor recreation industry focused on hiking,
15 wildlife watching, biking, paddling or other popular outdoor pursuits;
16 8. A representative of a statewide association representing hunters and anglers;
17 9. A representative of a statewide association representing recreational vehicle users;
18 10. A representative from the Department of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry,
19 Bureau of Parks and Lands;
20 11. A representative from the Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife's landowner
21 relations program; and
22 12. A representative from the Department of Economic and Community Development.
23 Sec. 3. Working group chairs. Resolved: That the Commissioner of Agriculture,
24 Conservation and Forestry or the commissioner's designee and the Commissioner of Inland
25 Fisheries and Wildlife or the commissioner's designee serve as cochairs of the working
26 group under section 1 and shall make appointments to the working group as outlined in
27 section 2. The cochairs shall serve as nonvoting members of the working group.
28 Sec. 4. Working group duties. Resolved: That the working group under section 1
29 shall:
30 1. Solicit and explore strategies to provide private landowners with financial incentives
31 to maintain and expand recreational access to important corridors and destinations;
32 2. Solicit input from a broad range of individuals and businesses involved in outdoor
33 and traditional recreational activities, landowners, outdoor recreation and public access
34 policy experts and the general public to understand the history and value of and issues
35 associated with the State's tradition of public access to public and private property;
36 3. Develop an assessment of the current and future status of public access to public and
37 private property, with particular attention to current and future outdoor and traditional
38 recreational activities;
39 4. Bring forth additional discussion points as agreed upon by the working group;
Page 2 - 132LR1460(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 538, L.D. 1308
1 5. Recommend actions and policies that may be implemented to better support public
2 access to public and private property in both municipalities and the unorganized territory;
3 and
4 6. Evaluate enforcement of existing laws and rules on designated state trail systems.
5 Sec. 5. Working group staff assistance. Resolved: That the departments shall
6 provide staffing to the working group under section 1 within existing resources and may
7 seek staffing and financial support from other state agencies and private entities to
8 accomplish the working group's work.
9 Sec. 6. Report. Resolved: That the departments shall report any findings and
10 recommendations resulting from meetings of the working group under section 1 to the Joint
11 Standing Committee on Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry and the Joint Standing
12 Committee on Inland Fisheries and Wildlife by February 15, 2026. Each of the committees
13 may report out a bill based on the report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd
14 Legislature.
15 Emergency clause. In view of the emergency cited in the preamble, this legislation
16 takes effect when approved.'
17 Amend the resolve by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or
18 section number to read consecutively.
19 SUMMARY
2200 The amendment replaces the resolve, changes the title and adds an emergency preamble
2211 and emergency clause. It directs the Department of Inland Fisheries and Wildlife and the
2222 Department of Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry to establish a working group that is
2233 broadly representative of landowner and land user interests to explore ways to maintain
2244 and expand public access to privately owned lands in the State. The departments are
2255 directed to report any findings and recommendations of the working group to the Joint
2266 Standing Committee on Agriculture, Conservation and Forestry and the Joint Standing
2277 Committee on Inland Fisheries and Wildlife by February 15, 2026. Each committee is
2288 authorized to report out a bill based on the report to the Second Regular Session of the
2299 132nd Legislature.
3300 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
